  "prompt": "Is the Russian Orthodox Church under the authority of the Russian State, technically?",
  "response": "The relationship between the Russian Orthodox Church and the Russian State is complex and has evolved over time. While the Russian Orthodox Church operates as an independent religious institution, it has historically had a close relationship with the state. \n\nIn contemporary Russia, the church enjoys significant influence and support from the government. The Russian Constitution guarantees freedom of religion, but in practice, the church and state are often seen as intertwined, with the church supporting state policies and the state providing the church with certain privileges. This relationship can sometimes lead to perceptions that the church is under the authority of the state, even though it maintains its own hierarchical structure and governance.\n\nIn summary, while the Russian Orthodox Church is technically independent, its close ties to the Russian State create a dynamic where the lines between religious authority and state influence can blur.",
